<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Parties, 1st Ld-Writethru,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Faithful Take Time to Party</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with Sunday evening parties;
PICKS UP 6th graf pvs bgng, `The biggest'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The air-conditioned walkway was the extravagance
most appreciated by the Democratic political leaders and Washington
media elite lingering by the mock newsstand bars at the Atlanta
newspapers' welcoming party Sunday night.
   ``Even the Ringling Brothers' tent isn't air conditioned,'' one
guest marveled at the Cox Enterprises Inc. party on the eve of the
Democratic National Convention.
   Dozens of invitation-only affairs and 56 parties for individual
state delegations kept thousands of delegates and journalists
entertained on the hot and humid day.
   Prospective Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis and
his family attended Ted Turner's crowded party at CNN Center, next
door to the convention site, before joining a family reunion hosted
by his cousin, Atlanta restaurateur Pano Karatassos.
   Massachusetts Sen. Ted Kennedy, dining at a separate party at
Karatassos' 103 West, stopped by to greet the families of Dukakis
and his vice presidential choice, Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen.
   Meanwhile, Jesse Jackson's fans jammed the ornate Fox Theater
for a fund-raising jazz and gospel concert, listening to music by
Nat King Cole's brother Freddie, an Atlanta resident, and others
for three hours before Jackson and his family arrived to rally the
faithful.
   Frigid air pumped into a tent spanning the short walkway between
the Woodruff Arts Center and the High Museum of Art cooled the
3,000 politicians and media honchos attending ``A Special Edition
Of Southern Hospitality,'' hosted by the parent company for The
Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution.
   The media chain, founded by 1920 Democratic presidential nominee
James Cox, apparently spared little expense for its party, filling
the tent and the lobbies of both buildings with bars and tables
overflowing with home-grown delicacies such as peach cheesecake.
   Sunday's partying completed a weekend of carousing by about
35,000 journalists, lobbyists, staffers, elected officials and
political junkies who have descended on Atlanta for the convention,
which opens Monday.
   All night Saturday, hotels were hopping, bars were packed and
lines extended out of dozens of nightclubs and restaurants along
Peachtree Street long past the normal closing time of 2 a.m.
   The horse-drawn carriages in the downtown hotel district were
doing a booming business as hundreds of people wandered streets
normally occupied in the early morning hours by the now-scarce
homeless.
   An overflow crowd from a heavy metal nightclub spilled onto
nearby railroad tracks, halting a train loaded with revelers. But
neither party missed a beat as the train retreated.
   Private parties ranged from a formal dinner-dance at the home of
Anne Cox Chambers, former U.S. ambassador to Belgium and chairwoman
of Atlanta Newspapers Inc., to an old fashioned ``stump speakin'''
with a real stump, mint juleps and ham biscuits, given by Betty
Talmadge, former wife of former Sen. Herman Talmadge, and Liz
Carpenter, former press secretary to Lady Bird Johnson.
   The biggest affair was a rock 'n' roll extravaganza for about
10,000 journalists at the Georgia World Congress Center, featuring
plenty of free liquor and dozens of dishes, ranging from hot dogs
and egg rolls to Brunswick stew and jambalaya.
   Bandstands scattered throughout the huge exhibition hall
showcased such acts as jazz artist Grover Washington,
rhythm-and-blues duo Ashford and Simpson and folk rocker Stephen
Stills.
   In a brief greeting, Mayor Andrew Young extended a special
welcome to the kid reporters for the Children's Express, whom he
called ``the only uncorrupted, honest, unbiased'' journalists in
the hall.
   Clearly he had missed seeing the Express reporter who raided a
fruit display, plopping whole pineapples into a plastic bag.
   ``We might get hungry later,'' the boy said.
   Atlanta's black community hosted a party for more than 250 black
elected officials from across the country at the white-columned
mansion of Atlanta businessman Nathaniel Goldston.
   Many of those revelers then joined former Atlanta Mayor Maynard
Jackson on his ``Midnight Train To Georgia,'' a fund-raiser on the
state-owned New Georgia Railroad to benefit Jackson's 1989 campaign
for another stint as mayor.
   Baseball stars Hank Aaron and Willie Stargell were among the
``celebrity conductors'' at a pre-ride party at the historic
Georgia Freight Depot, one of the city's few surviving pre-Civil
War buildings, before the train chugged out of the depot for an
18-mile loop around the city.
   During the trip, the crowd from Metroplex, a heavy metal
nightclub near, spilled onto the tracks. Rather than break up a
good party, the train turned around. Few at Jackson's party noticed
the difference.
   The ``in event'' Saturday probably was former President Jimmy
Carter's party for what he called ``my old friends _ and I use the
word carefully _ in the White House press corps.''
</TEXT>
