<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Meese-Intrigue Bjt   07-17 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Intrigue, Bjt,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negative Information Leaked About Two Former Meese Aides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Controversy follows Attorney General Edwin
Meese III everywhere he goes _ even out the door.
   The latest installment involves the leaking of unfavorable
information about two former Justice Department officials who have
been invited to testify before a Senate panel about their former
boss.
   Committee sources and sources close to the Justice Department
say the leaks were an attempt to discourage the two men from
testifying.
   Meese's resignation by itself may have convinced one of the men,
former Deputy Attorney General Arnold I. Burns, to resist the
committee's invitation to testify about Meese. Burns reportedly
believes Meese's stewardship is now ``ancient history.''
   But former criminal division chief William F. Weld, who along
with Burns suddenly announced his resignation March 29, is still
expected to appear July 26 before the Senate Judiciary Committee.
   Burns and Weld left March 29 when Meese was under intense
scrutiny from independent counsel James McKay, who was
investigating Meese's conduct on a number of ethics matters.
   The Democratic-controlled Judiciary Committee invited both men
to tell why they left, but neither would consider the request
before McKay completed his work.
   McKay submitted his still-secret findings on July 5 and, on the
same day, Meese announced that he would resign in late July or
early August. The committee then committee asked Burns and Weld to
testify on July 26. McKay's report was expected to made public on
Monday.
   Robert J. (Duke) Short, a committee aide to Sen. Strom Thurmond,
R-S.C., said he was asked by the committee's Democratic staffers
after Meese's resignation announcement to check whether Burns and
Weld were coming.
   According to Short, Burns told him ``the Meese story is now
ancient history, but if I'm subpoenaed, of course, I would
testify.'' A subpoena is highly unlikely, and as of now, Burns is
not expected to come.
   Weld described his conversation with Short in a startling letter
to the committee.
   Weld said that Short ``asked me whether there was an internal
Justice Department investigation of me in 1986 or 1987, based on an
anonymous letter alleging that I had smoked marijuana at a wedding
in 1982, and if so, whether that might not `complicate''' the
testimony.
   Weld pointed out an internal Justice Department investigation
found the allegation ``lacked merit,'' and in subsequent interviews
emphatically denied the marijuana incident.
   Short said he received a call about the marijuana allegation and
``asked Weld about it.''
   Asked if he was attempting to hint to Weld that he avoid
testifying, Short said in an interview, ``Absolutely not. Not under
any circumstance.''
   Furthermore, Short said, he made the calls to Weld and Burns at
the request of the Democratic committee staff because both men are
Republicans and Short knew them personally.
   Mark Gitenstein, chief counsel for the committee's Democratic
majority, supported Short. ``I don't believe Duke tried to
discourage Weld from testifying,'' he said. ``I don't believe that
was his intention.''
   But last week, the Washington Times carried a news story about
the marijuana allegation, and had previously published several
stories about Burns' efforts to get his former law partner a
federal judgeship.
   A Justice Department spokesman, Patrick Korten, said he had ``no
idea who is responsible for making any of that information
available.''
   As to the conflict-of-interest allegations, Stephen Markman, the
assistant attorney general in charge of screening judicial
candidates, said Burns was above board in his efforts on behalf of
his former partner, Stuart Summit _ now a nominee for the 2nd U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals.
   ``Obviously his name came to our attention because of his
relationship to Mr. Burns,'' Markman said. ``Mr. Burns probably
bent over backwards to make sure he wasn't viewed as pushing the
candidate to the exclusion of other candidates.
   ``Mr. Summit went through the normal procedures _ the regular
interview process, the regular background process, and final
approval by the attorney general. The attorney general was aware
that Summit was a partner of Arnie Burns. Burns' relationship with
Summit was quite open.''
</TEXT>
