<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     07-17 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrilla Leader Says Communists Willing To Open Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A guerrilla commander said Sunday
that communist rebels are willing to open new peace talks with
President Corazon Aquino's government.
   But Gregorio Rosal, a leader of the Meliton Glor communist rebel
faction on the main Luzon Island, said the offer must not be
considered an act of surrender.
   Rosal said the military has been sabotaging reconciliation
efforts by both the rebels and the government.
   ``We are ready to hold talks for the pursuit of long-lasting
peace, but never for surrender,'' Rosal said. ``The present
government is prone to saddling (us) with terms unacceptable for
free-wheeling talks, with the military ... acting as saboteurs to
any peaceful effort.''
   The representative of the New People's Army, the outlawed armed
branch of the Communist Party, made the statement in a
tape-recorded message sent to news agencies.
   Rosal did not say on what terms the rebels were willing to
negotiate.
   Rosal also represents the National Democratic Front, a 12-member
umbrella group that includes the Communist Party and its army.
   The communists, who claim 25,000 guerrillas are fighting for
them, have been waging a war for 19 years to establish a Marxist
state in the Philippines.
   About 10,000 people Sunday celebrated the second anniversary of
the founding of Alsa Masa (People's Uprising), an anti-communist
vigilante group.
   Chanting anti-communist slogans, the demonstrators burned
effigies of the rebels.
   Five communists and a provincial leftist leader were killed and
eight soldiers were wounded in separate insurgency-related clashes
in the past four days, the state-run Philippine News Agency
reported.
   It said government troops Saturday killed five guerrillas in a
gunfight on the outskirts of the town of Magalona on Negros Island,
about 300 miles southeast of Manila.
   In Bacolod, the main city on Negros, about 6,000 people gathered
Friday in front of the Sacred Heart Seminary to protest alleged
communist infiltration of the Roman Catholic Church, the agency
reported.
   It said the crowd demanded the resignation of Bacolod Bishop
Antonio Fortich, an outspoken advocate of human rights _ including
those of the rebels _and refused to allow the prelate and about 100
others to leave the building.
   Also in Bacolod, unidentified men Thursday gunned down Nilo
Piccio, the local chairman of the New Patriotic Alliance, a leftist
group. The assailants escaped.
   In another incident, the agency said eight soldiers were wounded
Friday when their vehicle struck a land mine on Panay Island. It
said troops captured two rebels in a brief firefight after the
incident.
</TEXT>
