<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Sikhs     07-17 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sikhs,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Sikhs, Three Police Killed In Shootout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHANDIGARGH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh militants clashed with police
Sunday in a gunfight that left three Sikhs and three police
officers dead, authorities said.
   The shooting began at about 3:30 a.m., after police tried to
break into a house in Chandigarh believed occupied by Sikh
militants, said police Superintendent R.P. Singh.
   The militants opened fire, killing Inspector Jagjit Singh and
injuring two police officers, who later died, the superintendent
said. Three militants were killed in the return fire.
   Chandigargh is the capital of Punjab state, where Sikh militants
are fighting to establish a Sikh homeland.
   In another incident in Punjab, three state employees were shot
and killed Saturday night near the city of Amritsar, the Press
Trust of India news agency reported. The victims included one Sikh
and two Hindus.
   Three moderate Sikhs were also killed by suspected militants in
other areas of Punjab on Saturday night, the agency said.
   The killings raise to 1,517 the number of people killed in
Punjab this year in the Sikhs' violent campaign.
   Sikhs form just 2 percent of India's 800 million people but are
a majority in Punjab. Radical Sikhs claim they are discriminated
against by the Hindus, who make up 80 percent of India's population.
</TEXT>
