<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-88 1330EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SnailHunt Bjt   07-17 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Snail Hunt, Bjt,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snails Sought To Revive Ancient Ritual</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orthodox Jews are scouring Israel's
Mediterranean beaches for a rare snail that produces a blue dye
they say is needed to revive a religious ritual abandoned 1,500
years ago.
   The snail hunt was prompted last week by Rabbi Menachem Burstin
of Jerusalem, who is trying to recreate a process once used to dye
a single thread of the Jewish prayer shawl in accordance with a
biblical command.
   Jews were forced to abandon the practice in the fifth century,
Burstin said, when Roman authorities banned all but the ruling
class from wearing colored clothing. The recipe for the dye they
used was lost.
   ``Now we are looking for it,'' said Burstin, of the prestigious
Mercaz Harav religious seminary. ``We want to revive the mitzva
(biblical command).''
   Israel's chief rabbis, who rule on religious issues, have not
given the go-ahead to renew the ancient practice and are awaiting
Burstin's findings before they consider it, said Zalman Quittner, a
spokesman for the rabbis.
   Interest in the mollusk mystery was roused when Burstin appealed
in a religious newspaper, ``Erev Shabat,'' for seminary students to
seek out the rare snail, known as the Janthina or ``violet snail''
because of its purple-blue color.
   Burstin said he has been deluged with reports of snail
sightings. But he has so far collected only a tenth of the
``bucketful'' he says is needed to extract enough dye to test his
theory.
   The 33-year-old rabbi is trying to validate a claim made in 1920
by the late Chief Rabbi Yitzhak Isaac Halevy Herzog, father of
President Chaim Herzog.
   In a doctoral thesis at the University of London, the elder
Herzog suggested the original dye used came from the Janthina
snail. But he noted the the snail seldom made it to Israeli shores.
   This summer, however, the snails have been sighted along with
schools of jellyfish that have been plaguing beaches, Burstin said.
   Hank Mienis, curator of the Hebrew University of Jerusalem
Mollusk Collection, said there are five species of the Janthina.
The largest are 1{ inches in diameter, he said.
   The ancient Jewish practice involved coloring one of eight
strands of a prayer shawl as a sign of devotion to God.
   The white prayer shawls have been worn under clothing by devout
Jewish men since the ancient Israelites roamed the desert with
Moses during their exodus from Egypt. It is customary to kiss one
of the fringes during portions of morning prayers.
   The Old Testament says that God ordered Moses:``Speak to the
children of Israel and tell them to make for themselves fringes on
the corners of their garments throughout their generations, and to
put on the fringe of each corner a blue thread.
   ``You shall have it as a fringe, so that when you look upon it
you will remember to do all the commands of the Lord, and you will
not follow the desires of your heart and your eyes which lead you
astray.''
   The Talmud, which interprets Jewish law, explained how the blue
fringe should be dyed but did not give the source of the dye.
Jewish sages have speculated about the recipe, but only began
trying to revive the custom about 100 years ago in Poland, Burstin
said.
   He said a Hasidic rabbi, Gershon Hanoch Leiner of Radzin,
maintained the dye came from a squid. About 17,000 followers of
Leiner used the method, he said, and many died at the hands of the
Nazis during World War II.
   Herzog differed with Leiner's followers by suggesting the
Janthina snail, and not the squid, was the true source of the dye.
   ``I am checking Herzog's method to the end,'' said Burstin, who
has been studying the issue for 14 years. ``We cannot push this
mitzva forward until we solve this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
