<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Hispanics     07-17 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Hispanics,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Hispanics Establish Political Group To Boost Unity,
Clout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 150 Hispanic Democrats founded a political
group of their own Sunday in an effort to galvanize the clout of
the nation's fastest-growing minority.
   ``We're here to demonstrate to the Democratic Party that we are
a community once and for all united,'' Rep. Esteban Torres of
California, a co-chairman of the group, told the Sunday morning
gathering. ``We're coming together here for the first time and it
will not be the last.''
   The group, called National Hispanic Democrats, is made up of
Mexican-Americans, Puerto Rican-Americans and Cuban-Americans.
   About 200 of the 4,200 delegates to this week's Democratic
National Convention are Hispanic.
   Hispanics have drawn acute attention from both parties this year
because their growing vote is concentrated in key states like
California, Texas and Florida. Both Democratic presidential
candidate-to-be Michael Dukakis and his Republican counterpart
George Bush have already pledged to appoint a Hispanic cabinet
member if elected.
   The group said it hopes to capitalize on that interest.
   ``What we have here is the most serious effort in recent times
to focus the Hispanic agenda,'' Torres said. ``Our challenge is not
the differences sometimes created by national origin or regional
bias but the similarities which over shadow our differences.''
   In the past, organizers said, differences among the different
segments of the Hispanic population have kept its clout fragmented.
The new group has agreed to disagree on some issues, but agrees on
the need for improvements in education, jobs, health care and crime
fighting as well as mobilizing the Hispanic vote in November.
   ``The time is right for this to work,'' said co-chair Marife
Hernandez, a Democratic Party activist from New York. ``We're going
to make sure that we're heard.''
</TEXT>
