<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-DamBurst     07-17 0145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Dam Burst,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dam Bursts, Air Force Called In</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 75-foot-high dam burst Sunday in
western India, stranding hundreds of villagers and isolating some
towns, the United News of India reported.
   The report said air force helicopters and police boats were
called in to rescue people.
   The news agency said contact could not be made with the village
of Trambau because it was isolated by waters from the burst dam. It
said 500 villagers were reported to be stranded on a hill. No loss
of life was reported, UNI said.
   The dam burst in the Rann of Kutch, a marshy area in Gujarat
state near Pakistan. It frequently dries out in the spring but
becomes almost an inland sea during the rainy season, which is
currently sweeping across India.
   The dam burst at Mithi in western Kutch, UNI said.
</TEXT>
