<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Richards     07-17 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Richards,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Richards Promises `Very Direct' Keynote Address</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas State Treasurer Ann Richards on Sunday
tried out the podium she will use for Monday night's keynote
address to the Democratic National Convention, and promised a
``very direct'' message in her own homespun style.
   ``It's my speech. No one has seen it, and no one has given me
advice,'' she said. ``I want to lay it all out and put it on a
level that everyone will understand.''
   Richards said she will direct her address to her parents in
Waco, Texas, and to a family in the same area who recently wrote
her a letter about their economic problems and concerns about
America's national pride.
   The 20-minute speech will be simple and will be sprinkled with
``Texanisms,'' she said, adding, ``I wish I were William Jennings
Bryan or Mario Cuomo, but I'm not.''
   Richards, the highest woman elected official in Texas and a
likely candidate for governor in 1990, is a staunch feminist, and
said her selection to deliver the high-profile keynote address has
jangled her nerves.
   ``I think it's one of the most difficult things I carry with me
all the time,'' she said. ``I feel very strongly that I don't want
to fail. I always want to do well because then they'll think,
`Well, she can do it, maybe some other women can, too.''
</TEXT>
