<FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-88 1430EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--UnderthePodium     07-17 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Under the Podium,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-CVN--Made for TV, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beneath the convention podium is a maze of rooms
where speakers try on clothes, get made up in plastic barber's
chairs, and rehearse their delivery as coaches warn: ``Don't get
carried away with the ad-libs.''
   ``We want to make sure people look easy and confident and not
uncomfortable,'' said Mike Sheehan, a Washington media consultant
and head coach. ``Many people will only be seeing this through the
eyes of a camera. I don't want (TV viewers) to be distracted.''
   The rehearsal room, identified by a green magic marker sign, is
one of several makeshift preparation areas beneath the podium.
There is a makeup room boasting two plastic barber's chairs and
some lights, a tastefully furnished conversation area draped off
from the cables and pre-stressed concrete beams, and a yellow and
white holding tent filled with a motley assortment of couches, end
tables and potted plants.
   Mirrors, telephones and portable toilets are also among the
amenities provided for those scheduled to speak. Texas Treasurer
Ann Richards, the keynote speaker, told reporters Sunday she was
going under the podium to try on jackets to see which color looked
best.
   The rehearsal room itself is equipped with a white plasterboard
replica of the podium, built to scale. A television screen provides
a simultaneous and sometimes unsettling view of speakers as they
rehearse. On either side of the podium is a TelePrompter mirror
reflecting the words of their speeches.
   Victor Raiser, the finance chairman of the Democratic National
Committee, had written the word ``turn'' into his speech at
periodic intervals as a reminder to shift his gaze from right to
left or vice versa.
   ``Once you get the hang of it, it's not so bad,'' Sheehan told
Raiser, trying to be encouraging. As Raiser launched into his brief
remarks for what seemed the millionth time, Sheehan paced, fidgeted
and adjusted the TelePrompTer.
   ``He's got it,'' he said suddenly to Dan Buck, assigned to
``punch up'' speeches and, sometimes, to cut them. ``How are we
doing?''
   ``3:40,'' Buck replied.
   ``We've got to pick up the pace,'' Sheehan said. He directed
Buck to do some trimming _ ``little surgicals'' _ and advised
Raiser, ``Don't get carried away with the ad-libs.''
   Sheehan, Buck and a battery of computer operators and
technicians started rehearsing people last Wednesday and won't be
finished until Thursday, the last day of the convention.
   ``We're not going to see the convention. We'll read about it in
Time magazine,'' said Buck, whose regular job is administrative
assistant to Rep. Patricia Schroeder of Colorado.
   ``By Thursday night I'll qualify for my voter registration card
at the Omni,'' said Sheehan. ``By the way, what's it like in the
outside world?''
   Replied Buck, ``Someone said it was snowing.''
</TEXT>
