<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-AirTraffic     07-17 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Air Traffic,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Unions Call Off Theatened Strike By Air Controllers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of three unions representing French air traffic
controllers on Sunday called off plans for a one-day strike, but
airlines said it would be too late to restore most canceled flights.
   French controllers called the strike for Monday to protest
conditions stemming from increased air traffic over Western Europe.
They say they are overworked and suffering from stress.
   Two unions representing about 70 percent of the air controllers
_ the National Union of Air Traffic Controllers and another known
as the CFDT _ said they were canceling the strike in response to a
letter Sunday from Transport Minister Michel Delebarre.
   Delebarre promised a series of meetings to find solutions to the
problems.
   But the Union of Civil Aviation Unions, affiliated with the
Communist-led General Federation of Labor, said the 16 percent of
controllers it represents would stay off the job.
   The union said Delabarre's letter was ``a gesture of good will''
but offered no new proposals.
   Officials of Air France and Air Inter, the state-owned
international and domestic airlines, said there was no time to
reschedule previously canceled flights.
   ``We've got the planes, but we have to put together the crews,''
said Air France spokesman Jean-Claude Couturier. ``There's also no
way to alert the passengers.''
   He said the airline did not expect to be able to restore very
many of the canceled flights.
   Earlier, Air France dropped 90 of its 138 flights scheduled to
leave Paris. Air Inter said it would cancel all but 80 of its 347
flights.
   Foreign airlines flying to and from France also canceled most of
their flights or diverted them to cities in Belgium, Switzerland or
Italy.
   The three unions have different demands, which include hiring
more controllers.
</TEXT>
