<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Chemical Fire,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Flee City As Chemical Tank Burns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MASSA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire engulfed a chemical storage tank in
northern Italy Sunday, producing a cloud of acrid black smoke that
prompted thousands of people to flee in panic, police said.
   No serious injuries were reported and authorities said the smoke
was not toxic.
   About 20 people complaining of stomach pains and burning in
their eyes and throats were examined at the hospital in Massa,
about 170 miles north of Rome on the Tyrrhenian coast.
   Police said an explosion of unknown origin sparked the fire in
the 13,000-gallon tank of cyclohexane, a liquid hydrocarbon.
   Black smoke filled the sky after the 6:30 a.m. blast and
thousands of people rushed to their cars and fled, causing huge
traffic jams, police said.
   Firefighters and police said the blaze was quickly brought under
control.
   The company is owned by Farmoplant, a subsidiary of the giant
Montedison chemical firm, the Italian news agency ANSA reported.
   In recent years there have been several toxic leaks at the
plant, and residents of Massa demanded its closure in a referendum
in October.
</TEXT>
