<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yemen-President     07-17 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yemen-President,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yemen President Resigns, Later Is Re-Elected</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   SAN`A, North Yemen (AP) _ President Ali Abdullah Saleh resigned
Sunday before a newly elected parliament but was re-elected within
hours, the official news agency said.
   The Saba news agency said the 159-member Majlis Al-Shura, or
consulative assembly, chose Saleh for a new five-year term. The
vote was 152 in favor, with two abstaining and five absent, it said.
   Saleh, 46, has governed the Red Sea country at the southern tip
of the Arabian Peninsula since July 1978.
   The news agency said he resigned during a speech in which he
told the new legislature to choose ``whoever they see capable,
efficient and sincere ... in shouldering the responsibility of
leading the country.''
   The assembly is the first elected parliament in the history of
North Yemen, which became a republic in 1962. In elections July 5,
128 members were elected, and Saleh later appointed 31 more members.
   Saleh's term was to expire in May, but the constituent assembly
overseeing the elections decided to extend it until August.
</TEXT>
