<HEAD>Polish Radio To Broadcast Radio Free Europe Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish radio will broadcast programs by
U.S.-funded Radio Free Europe in response to increased public
interest in the Western radio station, the state-run news agency
PAP said Sunday.
   The state-run radio station will air programs and discussions
that were recorded this year at the Munich-based Radio Free Europe,
the agency said.
   The purpose of the broadcasts is ``to enable Polish listeners to
form their own opinion on the character of Radio Free Europe and
the kind of its transmissions,'' the report said.
   Polish government spokesman Jerzy Urban and the official Polish
press have accused Radio Free Europe of inaccuracies and of
presenting a distorted view of Poland.
   In announcing the broadcasts, PAP said the public was interested
in ``the Western radio station's behind-the-stage subversive
activities.''
   Jamming of Polish-language broadcasts of Radio Free Europe,
Voice of America and the BBC ended January 1. The action was
accompanied by an increased Polish media campaign against the
stations, particularly Radio Free Europe, which currently broadcast
uncensored news and commentary to Poland.
