<HEAD>Ozal Says Ruling Party To Seek Early Local Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Turgut Ozal said Sunday that his
Motherland Party will try to amend the constitution to hold
nationwide local elections in October, five months ahead of
schedule.
   Ozal told a news conference that the decision to seek the
amendment was made at the end of a two-day meeting of his party's
Chairmanship Council which, in addition to himself, is made up of
eight top party officials.
   The support of at least 300 deputies in the 450-seat Parliament
is needed to pass the measure authorizing the early local elections.
   The Motherland Party has 290 seats in Parliament.
   The opposition True Path Party of former Premier Suleyman
Demirel, which has 59 deputies, has also repeatedly expressed
support for early local elections.
   Ozal mentioned Oct. 16 and Oct. 23 as possible dates for the
elections if the amendment is approved.
   The local elections will be a crucial test for Ozal's party,
whose popularity in recent months has slipped to about 25 percent,
down from the 36 percent the party enjoyed in last year's general
elections, according to public opinion polls.
