<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Convention Sidelights, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0755,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlanta Shows Many Faces on Eve of Convention</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS name of ice cream brand from Goprin's to Gorin's in
17th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This is what Atlanta has become:
   Suspicious:
   Before Jesse Jackson arrived at the Marriott Marquis Hotel,
grown men in dark suits pushed ball point pens into the soil of
hundreds of planters hanging off the balconies on each of 46
floors. This unusual method of aerating the soil was a check for
explosives.
   Helpful:
   The Iowa delegation, in a superbly crafted handbook, advises
conventioneers to wear light clothing _ good advice in 90 plus
temperatures _ and to wear comfortable shoes for considerable
walking on unforgiving concrete floors. The best advice of all,
however, is: ``Find the Rest Rooms. This will save time.''
   Hospitable:
   A sign at The Tattletale, a strip joint, reads: ``Welcome
delegates.'' But not all. One delegate to the Democratic National
Convention is 18 years old, too young for such educational
enterprises. Besides, Kristin Farr of Redmond, Wash., possibly
prefers other entertainments.
   A collector's paradise:
   One of the most active subcultures at the convention is the
button collector. He prowls the hard concrete of the Georgia World
Congress Center, where the news media do their work in
blue-curtained enclaves, sniffing out new sources the way a pig
goes for truffles. ``You got any buttons?'' has replaced ``When's
Jesse coming?'' as a topic. At The New York Times, more than a day
before the first sound of the gavel at the convention, a
hand-lettered sign frostily declared ``No More Buttons!''
   A protest site:
   A pro-marijuana group of hippies clad in tie-dyed garments is
staging the ``Alternative Convention '88'' just three blocks from
The Omni. Saturday was human rights day for the Alternatives.
Sunday was Animal Rights Day, and Monday will be particularly busy
as No Nukes, Native American Rights and Environmental Day complete
with music from the Plutonium Players.
   On Saturday, urine testing was a major point of contention for
the Alternative platform, and marijuana was touted as both a ``safe
drug'' and, in a hemp form, as a cheap source of paper products.
   Some 75 groupies heard philosopher and former drug guru Timothy
Leary say that at the Democratic convention, ``Ain't going to be no
one thinking for themselves.'' That did not keep him from showing
up at a convention party _ perhaps to check out the thinking.
   A walk down memory lane:
   The World Congress Center, home for 3,500 news people, is so big
that the fire department insisted on partitioning it with street
names. There is John F. Kennedy Boulevard, Lyndon B. Johnson
Avenue, Harry S. Truman Road and Latimore Lane. Latimore, a party
staff member, got in there, it is said, because they ran out of
Democratic presidential names. Non-winning nominees like George B.
McClellan, Horatio Seymour, Horace Greeley and Alton S. Parker
apparently never were considered.
   Demopolitically Aware:
   Gorin's ice cream put its analysis of the political situation
into its product, creating ``Dukakis Delight'' a mixture of
strawberry and chocolate _ those being the favorites of the
Massachusetts governor and his wife.
   Cynics suggested the Dukakis treat would typically be bland and
boring. There was no sign of Jesse Jackson Rainbow sherbet.
   Almost, but not quite ready:
   It was ever thus, but come opening day, Monday, for better or
worse, the 40th Democratic National Convention, the first in the
South since 1972, will open in a splash of rose, sky-blue and pink.
   Visitors are told those podium colors truly are patriotic, that
they will be the traditional red, white and blue to the folks
watching on TV. The delegate seats, however, are covered with the
real red, white and blue.
   The Omni, usually home to the Atlanta Hawks, may well be the
smallest hall for a Democratic political convention in modern
times. The scoreboard high overhead betrays its heritage, with ads
for Winston cigarettes, Coca-Cola _ the hometown product _ and
Delta Air Lines, which also makes its home here.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
