<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--VoterConcerns     07-17 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Voter Concerns,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Finds Economy, Family Issues Are Top Concerns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters ranked the economy their top concern _
followed by family issues and defense _ in a Gallup poll sponsored
by the nation's largest organization of retirees.
   Horace B. Deets, the executive director of the American
Association of Retired Persons, said Sunday the survey of 1,500
voters indicated ``family issues are especially important to
marginal or swing voters, including Democrats who voted for Reagan
in 1984.''
   The Gallup organization, in a telephone survey conducted June
14-19, asked voters to rate issues they regarded as ``one of the
most important factors determining your vote.''
   Almost two-thirds, 65 percent, picked economic issues. Forty-six
percent cited family issues, compared with 44 percent who said
defense and 36 percent foreign policy.
   Deets said nearly 500 of the 4,162 delegates to the Democratic
National Convention belong to the AARP, which boasts a membership
of 28 million people 50 and older.
   The organization held a briefing Sunday for several dozen
delegates on three of its main concerns: long-term care,
safeguarding Social Security and improving private pensions, and
health care costs.
   An AARP-Gallup analysis of the survey said, ``Older respondents
are more concerned about health care costs, retirement income and
the costs of long-term care. Younger respondents are more concerned
about employment opportunities, college costs, the costs of buying
a house and child care.''
</TEXT>
