<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Kirk     07-17 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Kirk,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kirk: Convention Like a TV Miniseries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Party Chairman Paul Kirk, in a
convention-eve pep talk, told state delegation leaders Sunday to
think of the convention as a four-day television miniseries with
the delegates as the live audience.
   ``We have worked together for four years for this week,'' he
said. ``Remember ... you never get a second chance to make a first
impression.''
   He asked the delegates to stay in their seats. ``For the people
who came to party, there is plenty of opportunity next door,'' Kirk
said.
   Next door to the Omni Coliseum, where the convention opens
Monday, is a huge hall whose rooms have been reserved for parties
and other events.
   The delegation leaders were told that each evening's convention
session should be regarded as two segments, the important one being
the two hours when ABC, CBS and NBC are putting it on the air.
   ``Between 9 and 11,'' the instruction went, ``we are going to
have to be jam up and jelly tight to get everything we want in
there.''
</TEXT>
