<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Protest, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0824,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White Supremacists March Called Off Amid Hostilities</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 17th graf pvs bgng, `They white,' to
UPDATE with Barrett comments; SUBS last grafs pvs with 7 grafs to
UPDATE with gay rights and animal rights demonstrations</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police determined to avoid ``blood in the
streets'' canceled a march and rally by white supremacists Sunday
after helmeted officers used riot shields to shove aside hundreds
of anti-racist demonstrators.
   The leader of the white supremacist group, the Nationalist
Movement, later was taken into protective custody by police.
   There was frequent shoving between police and
counterdemonstrators but no reports of violence or injuries outside
the Georgia state Capitol, where the opposing groups gathered. The
spot is a half-mile from the Omni, where the Democratic National
Convention opens Monday.
   The entire Capitol was roped off as anti-racist contingents were
confined to either end of Washington Avenue, separated by police in
riot gear. As temperatures rose above 90, the protesters,
representing a variety of groups, chanted such slogans as ``No KKK,
no Fascist USA.''
   An American flag and a Confederate flag were burned in the
street as hundreds of reporters looked on. Bare-chested, shaggy
youths danced wildly and chanted as others beat drums and played
flutes.
   Police with helmets and riot shields pushed the crowd back at
one point. Firecrackers popped and mounted police moved in, then
left the area.
   ``This was a hostile, angry, nasty crowd and that's why we
canceled the march,'' said Public Safety Commissioner George Napper.
   ``It was a tough call because this is America,'' he said, but he
said he was determined to avoid ``blood in the streets of Atlanta.''
   After the cancellation, about 250 counterdemonstrators marched
from the Capitol to the official protest zone near the convention
center, chanting ``We just took the Klan's march.''
   Gov. Joe Frank Harris said he did not think the cancellation
amounted to a failure of security.
   ``I think that shows the system worked,'' he said. ``We're here
to provide security for the people and also to protect them and to
see that everybody has a good time and nobody gets hurt.''
   Convention security spokeswoman Jackie Barrett said Richard
Barrett, chief organizer of the Nationalist Movement march and no
relation, was taken into protective custody when he entered the
protest zone.
   About 30 of his backers carrying Confederate battle flags tried
to march to the protest zone despite the cancellation. The
anti-racist protesters surrounded them but police separated the two
groups again before there was any violence. The white supremacist
marchers were then taken back to their cars by police bus, and
there were no arrests, police said.
   ``If our Lord Jesus can ride into Jerusalem on the back of a
donkey, Richard Barrett can drive down Marietta Street in his
Chevrolet pickup truck,'' protested Barrett before he was taken
into custody.
   ``This is a shameful act on the part of the city,'' said Gene
Guerrero, executive director of the American Civil Liberties Union
of Georgia, regarding the cancellation. The ACLU has gone to court
several times on behalf of white supremacists' free speech rights.
   ``The presence of 200 counterdemonstrators is no reason to
cancel the United States Constitution,'' he said. ``That's the same
argument (they) used to cancel civil rights demonstrations in the
1960s.''
   ``They (white supremacists) wanted to have a rally on this very
spot,'' said Andre Powell of Baltimore, a member of the All
Peoples' Congress, one of the anti-racist groups. ``And look who's
here. We feel it's very important that when the Klan comes out,
they must always know that people won't idly sit by.''
   Barrett said in a telephone interview that he was held at the
Fulton County Jail for four hours in what he called ``police
oppression.''
   ``Freedom isn't free, and sometimes you've got to pay the
price,'' said Barrett, who said his pickup truck was vandalized
while he was in jail. ``I paid mine today. But like Douglas
MacArthur, I shall return.''
   Barrett said he planned to hold a news conference Monday morning
in the Forsyth County seat of Cumming, site of a huge civil rights
protest in January 1987, to discuss the incidents Sunday.
   Sunday marked the first day of scheduled protests in the
two-acre parking lot across the street from the convention where
city authorities are providing a stage and sound equipment for
groups to demonstrate at two-hour intervals.
   About 20 people _ not including reporters _ showed up in
broiling heat as the Coalition to Support Cuban Detainees began the
protests. The Mad Housers, a homeless relief group based in
Atlanta, built a small red, white and blue hut as an example of the
structures they put up for homeless people in the city.
   About 120 people carrying signs and chanting slogans marched
from Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium to the protest zone to
demonstrate against Ethiopian control of the Eritrean region of
north Africa.
   In other demonstrations:
   _LEGAL, a gay rights group, pressed for more efforts to cure
AIDS and for an end to discrimination against homosexuals. Sen.
Alan Cranston, D-Calif., a sponsor of major AIDS funding
legislation, told a crowd of about 2,000 people, ``We must not be
overly cautious in battling this killer'' and urged more
experimentation with different possible cures for AIDS.
   Ray Hill of Houston, Tex., a gay rights activist for 26 years,
said the Democratic Party ``is not as sensitive to the brothers and
sisters who have died of AIDS as you and I have become.''
   Many demonstrators wore pink triangles similar to those Adolph
Hitler forced homosexuals to wear in Nazi Germany.
   _Radio personality Casey Kasem was among the speakers for
Compassion Campaign '88, an animal rights group. The organization
is promoting legislation to outlaw steel-jawed leg traps, use of
``veal cages'' that hold calves immobile to keep their flesh
tender, and some chemical tests on animals.
   ``We can begin to start thinking about stopping wars when we
stop killing the creatures we share the earth with, the animals,''
said Kasem, who hosts a nationally syndicated Top 40 radio program.
   _A planned march and rally by the Association of Community
Organizations For Reform Now was canceled because the heat was too
intense for some for the group's elderly members.
</TEXT>
