<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Kinnock     07-17 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Kinnock,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports Kinnock Held At Gunpoint In Zimbabwe Mix-Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NYANGA, Zimababwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers detained British Labor Party
leader Neil Kinnock at gunpoint Sunday after the Zimbabwe air force
plane in which he was traveling landed at a military airstrip 20
miles from the official welcoming party.
   Kinnock's wife Glenys, three Labor Party officials and a dozen
accompanying journalists also were detained at the remote airstrip
near Mutare, Zimbabwe, on the border with Mozambique.
   The plane bringing Kinnock's party from Mozambique landed at the
airstrip while Zimbabwe government officials and British High
Commissioner Ramsay Melhuish were at Mutare's civilian airport,
Grand Reef, about 20 miles away.
   At the military strip, five soldiers armed with automatic rifles
escorted Kinnock and his entourage in a hut and detained them for
an hour until Melhuish and Zimbabwean officials arrived.
   Soldiers trained AK-47 weapons on Kinnock's group while it was
waiting.
   Kinnock told a corporal in camouflage fatigues that he would
lodge an official protest.
   Kinnock's party and British High Commission officials refused
further comment.
   In London, a Foreign Office spokesman said in London ``it all
appears to have been a hiccup. Mr. Kinnock and the party are now
continuing with their programs.''
   After the incident, Kinnock and the British officials drove to
Nyanga, a mountain resort 175 miles northeast of the capital
Harare. The labor leader was scheduled to visit a military camp
near Nyanga on Monday, where British soldiers are training
Zimbabwean and Mozambiquan troops.
   Kinnock is also expected to meet with Zinmbabwean President
Robert Mugabe later Monday before returning to Britain at the end
of a ten-day, four-nation southern African tour.
   Soldiers routinely guard civilian and military airstrips in
Zimbabwe. Security has been increased since the June 30 theft of a
Zimbabwe air force helicopter for an abortive attempt to rescue
alleged South African agents from jail.
   Kinnock's Labor Party is the main opposition party in Britain's
House of Commons. Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative
Party has held power since 1979.
   On his visit to Botswana, Mozambique, Zambia and Zimbabwe,
Kinnock said Mrs. Thatcher and her Western allies failed to put
enough pressure on South Africa to end its legal syustem of racial
separation and it alleged destabilization of neighboring
black-governed states.
</TEXT>
