<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0778 07-17 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0778,0671</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dutch Leader Begins Visit, Soldier Kills Palestinian</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 6-10 ``Lubbers said...he wrote.'' with 5 grafs
updating with later comments by Lubbers and Shamir. Pick up 11th
graf pvs: ``In the...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dutch Prime Minister Ruud Lubbers on Sunday
began a visit to Israel that was expected to create friction over
the crackdown on Palestinian demonstrators. A soldier shot and
killed a Palestinian who allegedly tried to grab his rifle.
   Also Sunday, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres appeared to break new
ground by saying he was willing to negotiate separately with
Palestinian representatives. Previously, Peres and other leaders
have called for talks with a joint Jordanian-Palestinian delegation.
   Lubbers was the most senior foreign leader to visit the Jewish
state since the Palestinian uprising began Dec. 8.
   The Dutch leader hinted from the outset he would be critical of
Israel's handling of the uprising in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip, in which 223 Palestinians and four Israelis have been
killed.
   ``To disagree is a privilege of friends,'' Lubbers said during a
welcoming ceremony near Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's office.
``We are with you even if we speak up. We speak up because we are
with you.''
   Later, at a state dinner given by Shamir, Lubbers said of the
Israeli response to the uprising: ``The harsh measures that have
been taken in attempting to normalize the situation have left
disturbing images in the minds of many of Israel's friends.''
   He also called on Israel to participate in an international
Middle East peace conference that would be under United Nations
auspices and to withdraw from the occupied lands in exchange for
peace. ``Claiming peace but denying land will be in our view
incompatible,'' he said.
   Shamir opposes an international peace conference that would
include the Soviet Union and the four other permanent members of
the U.N. Security Council, saying concessions would be demanded
that would jeopardize the Jewish state. Shamir, head of the
right-wing Likud bloc, also has said Israel would not withdraw from
the occupied territories.
   Shamir acknowledged he disagreed with the Dutch leader on some
Middle East issues but said he hoped the Netherlands would defend
Israel against the ``campaign of vilification that is being waged
against us on that continent.''
   Earlier Sunday, Lubbers met with Shamir for about 30 minutes and
they agreed to postpone working discussions until Monday, Israeli
officials said.
   In the latest violence, a soldier in the Israeli town of Petach
Tikva fatally shot a Palestinian after the man jumped him from
behind, grabbed his throat and tried to steal his rifle, police
said.
   The soldier, Yossi Hadas, 18, said he was waiting at a busy
intersection to hitch a ride to his base when he was assaulted.
   ``An Arab jumped me from behind,'' Hadas told Israel army radio.
``I jabbed my elbow into his ribs, pushed him aside, moved away,
put my magazine inside, cocked the rifle and fired.''
   Petach Tikvah police commander Yaacov Shoval said the assailant
tried to strangle the soldier as he grabbed the rifle.
   The assailant, a 21-year-old West Bank resident, died of a
gunshot wound in the chest at nearby Beilinson Hospital, police
said. Israel radio gave his name as Yassin Mahazou.
   The radio report quoted police as saying the attacker apparently
planned to kidnap the soldier. It said another Palestinian was
arrested in connection with the attack.
   Also Sunday, troops opened fire on stone-throwing Palestinians
in the West Bank village of Qabatiyeh, wounding an 18-year-old Arab
in the leg, officials at nearby Al Ittihad Hospital in Nablus said.
The army said it was checking the report.
   Peres, head of the left-of-center Labor Party, told Israel
television that ``we are willing to negotiate separately with the
Palestinians,'' but emphasized such talks would not include the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Israel refuses to negotiate with the PLO, which it considers a
terrorist group.
</TEXT>
