<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Bus Crash,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Buses Crash, 38 Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bus braking to avoid three cows
crossing a road was struck in the rear by another bus in foggy
weather Sunday and 38 people were killed, police reported.
   They said dozens of passengers were injured in the accident but
they did not have the exact figure.
   The bus that was rear-ended went off the road and into a lake
and many of the victims drowned when they were trapped in the
partially submerged vehicle, according to police. They said all of
the bodies were recovered and there were no foreigners on either
bus.
   All of the people who perished were on the first bus that was
carrying 50 passengers, according to the television network TV
Globo. It said there were 45 passengers aboard the second bus.
   Police spokesman Elias Campos said the buses were making the
335-mile trip from Londrina in the southern state of Parana to an
industrical center near Campinas when the accident occurred.
   ``It was early morning, foggy and the road is narrow,'' said
Campos who was contacted by telephone in Piracicaba, a town 165
miles west of Sao Paulo and near the site of the accident.
   ``Three cows crossed the road, the first driver braked suddenly
and the second smashed into the back of the bus, pushing the first
vehicle into a roadside lake,'' Campos said.
   He said both bus drivers survived.
</TEXT>
