<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0816,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rainy Storms In East, But HOT There And California</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 3rd graf to UPDATE with possible
tornado in Pottstown, Pa. Picks up 4th graf pvs `A weak...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms spread rain over parts of the central Plains, the
South and the Northeast on Sunday, and more high temperature
records were toppled in the East and in California, where even San
Francisco topped 100 degrees.
   A low pressure system over northwestern Oklahoma scattered
thunderstorms with generous rain over much of Kansas and into parts
of western Missouri. El Dorado, Kan., got 2.52 inches of rain in a
day and a half and other parts of central and eastern Kansas got up
to 2 inches of rain in 24 hours.
   Thunderstorms rumbled over parts of New York state, Vermont and
north-central Pennsylvania while a cold front slowly moved into the
area. Rochester, N.Y., got more than an inch and a quarter of rain
in an hour during the morning, and Elmira, N.Y., got wind gusts to
54 mph. Buffalo, N.Y., got 1.39 inches of rain in the six hours up
to 2 p.m. EDT.
   The roofs of an apartment building and a house in Pottstown,
Pa., were ripped off Sunday night by what local authorities
described as a tornado. No injuries were reported. The National
Weather Service said radar showed there were several severe
thunderstorms in the area, but that no tornado was confirmed.
   A weak low pressure system anchored over extreme southern
Alabama spread showers and thunderstorms from the lower Mississippi
Valley through the central and eastern Gulf Coast, and Pensacola,
Fla., got 2.53 inches of rain during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT.
   Philadelphia hit a record high of 103 degrees, also setting a
record for the number of consecutive days in a year of 100-degree
temperatures. Sunday was the fifth day in a row that the area
posted a temperature of 100 degrees or better.
   Downtown Baltimore reached a record 103, and that was a record
eighth time this year that the city has hit 100 degrees or better.
   Other record highs were 97 at Allentown, Pa.; and 101 at
Baltimore-Washington International Airport; while Huntington,
W.Va., tied its record of 100 and Newark, N.J., tied its record of
99.
   Parts of California also were heating up while high pressure
built up off the Pacific Coast. It took one hour for the
temperature to jump 10 degrees to a record 84 in downtown San
Francisco, and the city later climbed to 103, the hottest there for
any time of year in about 125 years of record-keeping.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 61
degrees at Whidbey Island, Wash., to 110 at Needles, Calif. Sunday
morning's low was 37 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Monday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the central high Plains through the lower Missouri and middle
Mississippi valleys, the lower Ohio and Tennessee valleys, the
middle and southern Atlantic Coast into the central and eastern
Gulf Coast and Florida.
   Highs in the upper 70s were predicted across north-central
Montana, and across the northern parts of the northern Plains and
upper Mississippi Valley; around 100 across southwestern Oklahoma
and central Texas into the Rio Grande Valley; between 100 and 110
in the desert Southwest and the California valleys, but up to 115
in the southern and northern valleys of California; and in the 80s
or 90s across much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
