<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SwaggartCrusade 1stLd-Writethru a0830 07-17 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Swaggart Crusade, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0830,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Organizers Expect Thousands To Attend Swaggart Crusade</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS in 3rd graf to prostitute in suburban New Orleans
sted Baton Rouge</NOTE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The organizer of Jimmy Swaggart's first
crusade outside his home state since the evangelist was defrocked
said he expects thousands of followers to defy the Assemblies of
God church and attend the event.
   The Rev. Mike Baldock, pastor of the independent New Covenant
Church and organizer of the July 22-24 crusade at Market Square
Arena, says he believes about 8,000 people will attend each of the
three meetings planned this weekend.
   Swaggart has not preached outside Louisiana since February, when
he tearfully admitted sinning against God and his family. A
prostitute in suburban New Orleans said Swaggart, of Baton Rouge,
paid her to perform lewd acts.
   The Assemblies of God dismissed Swaggart on April 8, after he
refused an order to refrain from preaching for a year and receive
professional counseling. He returned to the pulpit of his
independent ministry May 22.
   Juleen Turnage, a spokeswoman at the Assemblies of God
headquarters in Springfield, Mo., said individual pastors must
decide whether to support the Indianapolis crusade.
   Officials of the Northwest Assembly of God Church here ``made a
decision not to cooperate'' with the crusade in any way, said
Lucille Sexton, an aide to the Rev. Blanche Fiscus.
   ``Pastors have had instructions'' from the national and state
offices of the Assemblies of God not to have anything to do with
Swaggart activities, Sexton said.
   ``I would be surprised if any Assemblies of God people
attended,'' she added.
   The Rev. Charles Shank, district superintendent of the
Pentecostal denomination, also said pastors have been advised not
to support or cooperate with Swaggart.
   ``He has been disciplined by the church and isn't part of our
fellowship,'' Shank said.
   Baldock said he has had no trouble recruiting more than 500
volunteers, 200 ushers and a security force to help with the
weekend revival meetings.
   ``Market Square Arena provides a security force (for the arena),
but we provide one for the security of Brother Swaggart,'' he said.
   ``You always end up with some people who are hecklers,'' Baldock
said, adding that he is concerned some people might try to bring
banners derogatory to Swaggart into the arena.
   The Rev. Delores Fisher of the non-denominational Bethel Chapel
said she believes many members of the Assemblies of God will turn
out for Swaggart.
   ``I think a lot of them will go,'' she said. ``Preachers are no
different from the laity. They shouldn't be scorned because they
are human.''
</TEXT>
