<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Jackson-PAC 1stLd-Writethru a0855 07-17 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Jackson-PAC, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0855,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Launches Fund-Raising Effort for Political Action
Committee</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to correct that Ms. Hamer led credentials
battle to seat Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson transformed a Sunday evening
reception by the Democratic National Committee's Black Caucus to
honor civil rights heroes into a fund-raiser for a political action
committee he intends to develop after the convention ends this week.
   Jackson said the PAC will focus on economic issues, the 1990
census and reapportionment of congressional districts.
   He set the goal of raising $2 million in 400 contributions of
$5,000 apiece to form the ``Keep Hope Alive PAC.'' Staffers began
distributing enrollment forms and envelopes for contributions, and
he said $100,000 already had been raised a week ago.
   ``We get our mandate from Fannie Lou Hamer, ... from Dr. (Martin
Luther) King,'' he said in a pre-emptive defense of the formation
of the PAC. Ms. Hamer led and won a credentials battle at the 1968
convention to seat members of the Mississippi Democratic Freedom
Party instead of the regular state delegation.
   He said the PAC's goal would be to get more blacks and other
minorities to run for office.
   ``Only by running are you going to open up this process,'' he
told the crowd of about 500 at the Atlanta Life Insurance building
who had come to pay tribute to the ``Drum Majors of the Dream.''
   Eight individuals, including Jackson, the Rev. Ralph Abernathy,
Myrlie Evers, Coretta Scott King, Georgia Rep. John Lewis, the Rev.
Joseph Lowery, Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young and Rosa Parks were
honored for their roles in the civil rights movement of the '60s.
   With former rival Sen. Albert Gore Jr. at the podium, Jackson
spoke pointedly about the tensions and negotiations going on
between his campaign staff and those of the all-but-certain
Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis.
   ``We are at a moment of deliberation, development and
challenge,'' he said. ``We are just an attitude away from the White
House.''
   In a reference to Dukakis, he said the issues facing the
Democratic Party were bigger than any one person.
   ``The issue is having a seat in the budget next January. We can
cut the defense budget without cutting our defense,'' he said.
   He acknowledged that the right wing of the party had been
accommodated in Dukakis' selection of Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen as
his running mate but said, ``You need two wings to fly.''
   ``We can afford to lose a vote on the floor but not our
integrity,'' he added.
   Jackson also warned that the PAC would hold accountable those
Democratic officeholders coming to the convention as super
delegates from areas where he won a significant percentage of the
vote in the primaries and caucuses.
   ``We must visit those senators and governors whose states we won
but are not voting for us and find out what their plans are for the
future for private and public life.''
</TEXT>
