<HEAD>Dukakis, Bentsen Dine At Dukakis Kin's Restaurant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis celebrated his
first night in Atlanta at a private family Sunday dinner hosted by
one of his cousins, a well-known restaurateur.
   Dukakis, his wife Kitty and their children were joined at the
restaurant, 103 West, by Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, Dukakis'
designated running mate.
   The two men _ who arrived Sunday in Atlanta for the Democratic
National Convention beginning Monday _ were in a private room at
the restaurant while downstairs, Massachusetts Sen. Edward Kennedy
held another private party. Also dining at the restaurant was Sen.
Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii.
   Elaine LaMontagne, a spokeswoman for the restaurant, said Pano
Karatassos, the owner, is a second cousin of Dukakis. Their
grandmothers were first cousins, LaMontagne said.
   ``They keep in touch with what the families are doing,'' she
said.
   Karatassos, who was born in Savannah and moved to Atlanta about
10 years ago, has been active in the Dukakis campaign since the
Massachusetts governor announced his drive for the presidential
nomination.
   The six-course meal consisted of lump crab cake, gazpacho,
grapefruit sorbet, Maine lobster and red snapper ragout in a
sauterne wine sauce, fresh fruit, assorted pastries and ice cream.
