<HEAD>Rescue Workers Pull 55 Bodies From Wreck Of Amazon Ferryboat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crowded Amazon ferryboat that
crashed into a partially submerged wreck near the northeastern port
of Belem has left at least 55 dead, officials said Sunday.
   About 50 people were pulled from Belem Bay shortly after the
accident Friday night, but Robert Silva, a Belem port authority
spokesman, said as many as 70 people may have drowned.
   As night fell Sunday, volunteers and the coast guard suspended
efforts to look for more survivors.
   The ferry, with a capacity of 60 people, drifted off course into
an area known as the ``boat cemetery'' as the captain tried to
avoid what he thought was a coast guard launch, according to the
Jornal do Brasil newspaper.
   According to the daily, the same boat received several citations
recently for traveling overloaded.
   The ferry was headed from Belem 2,070 miles north of Rio to the
nearby island of Marajo, located near the mouth of the Amazon river.
